Follow-up for contingency table test

chisq_pairwise.Rd

Follow-up for contingency table test

chisq_pairwise(Xsq, population_in_row = TRUE, adjust = p.adjust.methods, ...)

chisq_residual(Xsq, adjust = p.adjust.methods)

Arguments

Xsq

Result from chisq.test()
population_in_row

Comparisons by row? (If not, by column.)
adjust

Method for correcting p-values. See stats::p.adjust.
...

Passed to chisq.test().

Examples

M <- as.table(rbind(c(762, 327, 468),
                    c(484, 239, 477)))
dimnames(M) <- list(
  gender = c("F", "M"),
  party = c("Democrat", "Independent", "Republican")
)
M
#>       party
#> gender Democrat Independent Republican
#>      F      762         327        468
#>      M      484         239        477

res <- chisq.test(M)
chisq_pairwise(res)
#>   comparison   Chi.sq df        p.raw       p.holm
#> 1    F vs. M 30.07015  2 2.953589e-07 2.953589e-07
chisq_pairwise(res, population_in_row = FALSE)
#>                   comparison    Chi.sq df        p.raw       p.holm
#> 1   Democrat vs. Independent  1.717892  1 1.899646e-01 1.899646e-01
#> 2    Democrat vs. Republican 29.059545  1 7.018745e-08 2.105623e-07
#> 3 Independent vs. Republican  9.335659  1 2.247373e-03 4.494746e-03
chisq_residual(res)
#>   gender       party    z.value       p.raw      p.holm
#> 1      F    Democrat  2.1988558 0.027888180 0.083664539
#> 2      M    Democrat -2.5046695 0.012256586 0.049026346
#> 3      F Independent  0.4113702 0.680801124 1.000000000
#> 4      M Independent -0.4685829 0.639367769 1.000000000
#> 5      F  Republican -2.8432397 0.004465747 0.022328734
#> 6      M  Republican  3.2386734 0.001200870 0.007205219
